        {
    "action": "Final Answer",
    "action_input": "In Java, a class is a blueprint from which individual objects are created. It's essentially a template that describes the state and behavior that the objects of the class all share. An object is an instance of a class. When you define a class, you specify the fields (variables) and methods (functions) that will determine the state and interaction of the objects. In Java, classes also define access specifiers which control the visibility of class members. For your studies, it's important to understand that classes are foundational to Java's object-oriented programming principles, encapsulating data for reuse and easy maintenance."
}
